{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514977","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514977"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:28:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:28:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12409"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12409"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.17,0.71,0.04,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4917"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110162"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4917"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2023-01-25T17:34:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-19T15:55:50+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2023-02-03T06:54:37+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 12:18:18"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12409"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"12201"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"5197"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92460"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"471"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4977"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11626"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8041"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8050"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16441"},{"type":"contributions","id":"41293"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42752"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92460"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110162","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110162"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of nausea, vomiting, and diarrhoea. His wife reports that he has become increasingly confused over the past 24 hours and is having difficulty recognizing family members. He has also complained of seeing yellow halos around lights. Four days ago, he developed a high fever and was diagnosed with pyelonephritis by his general practitioner, who prescribed ciprofloxacin 500mg twice daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis past medical history includes hypertension, heart failure, and chronic kidney disease. His regular medications include perindopril 2.5mg daily, carvedilol 3.125mg twice daily, spironolactone 25mg daily, and digoxin 125microg daily.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 46/min and irregular, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. There are some basal crackles on pulmonary auscultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESerum creatinine: 280 \u03bcmol/L (reference range 60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium: 5.8 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDigoxin level: 3.2 ng/mL (0.5-2.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium level 134 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute delirium","Uraemic encephalopathy","Digoxin toxicity","Ciprofloxacin-induced psychosis","Hyponatraemic encephalopathy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation is most consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Edigoxin toxicity\u003C/strong\u003E. The symptoms described, including nausea, vomiting, confusion, and visual disturbances (yellow halos), are classic signs of digoxin toxicity. The bradycardia (pulse rate 46/min) and irregular rhythm are also typical cardiac manifestations. The elevated digoxin level of 3.2 ng/mL, which is above the therapeutic range, confirms the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the digoxin toxicity has likely been precipitated by acute kidney injury, as evidenced by the markedly elevated serum creatinine (280 \u03bcmol/L). Digoxin is primarily eliminated by the kidneys, and any impairment in renal function can lead to accumulation of the drug and subsequent toxicity. The patient\u0027s pyelonephritis has likely caused acute kidney injury, leading to reduced digoxin clearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute delirium\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered, but the specific symptoms (especially visual changes) and the elevated digoxin level point more directly to digoxin toxicity as the cause of the confusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUraemic encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E is a possibility given the patient\u0027s elevated creatinine, but it typically occurs at much higher levels of renal impairment. The specific symptoms and elevated digoxin level make digoxin toxicity a more likely diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECiprofloxacin-induced psychosis\u003C/strong\u003E is rare and would not explain the other symptoms such as bradycardia and visual disturbances.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHyponatraemic encephalopathy\u003C/strong\u003E could cause confusion. However, the patient\u0027s almost normal sodium would not be a likely cause of hyponatraemic encephalopathy. Furthermore, the lack of symptoms (seizures, impaired level of consciousness) make the diagnosis unlikely. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of digoxin toxicity in this case would involve discontinuing digoxin, correcting electrolyte imbalances (particularly the hyperkalaemia), and considering the use of digoxin-specific antibody fragments (Digibind) if severe toxicity is present. The underlying acute kidney injury should also be addressed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Digoxin toxicity can occur due to acute renal injury, as the drug is primarily eliminated by the kidneys.","Common symptoms of digoxin toxicity include gastrointestinal disturbances, visual changes, and neurological symptoms such as confusion.","Elderly patients and those with pre-existing renal impairment are at higher risk of digoxin toxicity."],"references":["Diagnosis and practical management of digoxin toxicity: a narrative review and consensus statement. Andrews, Paula; Anseeuw, Kurtb; Kotecha, Dipakc,d; Lapostolle, Fr\u00e9d\u00e9rice; Thanacoody, Rubenf","Hyponatraemia. Perth Children\u0027s Hospital. November 2021. Available from: https://pch.health.wa.gov.au/For-health-professionals/Emergency-Department-Guidelines/Hyponatraemia"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92460"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12409"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92460"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-28T19:10:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-28T19:11:15+09:30","number":12,"notes":"typo corrected, some additions made to explanation","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"it